ory and to use custom.html as the default template name.\",\n        \"response\": \"To create a database in MariaDB using the terminal in Ubuntu, follow these steps:Connect to the MariaDB server:Copy codemysql -u username -p\\nReplace username with your MariaDB username. You will be prompted to enter your password.Create the database:Copy codeCREATE DATABASE database_name;\\nReplace database_name with the name of the database you want to create.Verify that the database was created:Copy codeSHOW DATABASES;\\nThis command will show a list of all the databases on the MariaDB server. The new database should be included in the list.Quit the MariaDB prompt:Copy codeQUIT\\nThat's it! You have now created a new database in MariaDB. You can use the USE command to select the database and start creating tables and inserting data.I hope this helps. If you have any questions or need further assistance, please don't hesitate to ask.\"\n    },\n    {\n        \"message\": \"`home.html` page is now working as i put it in the respective `templates` folder but when i click on `Upload an advertisement` it gives me this error : ```Internal Server Error\\nThe server encountered an internal error and was unable to complete your request. Either the server is overloaded or there is an error in the application.```\",\n        \"response\": \"To save the data from the upload.html form to the displayad database and the uploaded file to the displyaAdData folder, you will need to do the following:In the upload.html file, add a form with the necessary input fields for the data you want to save. For example:Copy code<form action=\\\"/upload\\\" method=\\\"post\\\" enctype=\\\"multipart/form-data\\\">\\n  <label for=\\\"ad_name\\\">Ad Name:</label><br>\\n  <input type=\\\"text\\\" id=\\\"ad_name\\\" name=\\\"ad_name\\\"><br>\\n  <label for=\\\"ad_description\\\">Ad Description:</label><br>\\n  <textarea id=\\\"ad_description\\\" name=\\\"ad_description\\\"></textarea><br>\\n  <label for=\\\"ad_file\\\">Select a file:</label><br>\\n  <input type=\\\"file\\\" id=\\\"ad_file\\\" name=\\\"ad_file\\\"><br><br>\\n  <input type=\\\"submit\\\" value=\\\"Submit\\\">\\n</form>\\nThis form has three input fields: ad_name, ad_description, and ad_file. The ad_file field is a file input field, which allows the user to select a file to upload.In the Flask backend, create a route to handle the form submission. This route will receive the form data and the uploaded file, and save them to the database and the file system:Copy codefrom flask import Flask, request, redirect, url_for\\nimport os\\nimport mysql.connector\\n\\napp = Flask(__name__)\\n\\n# Connect to the database\\ncnx = mysql.connector.connect(user='username', password='password',\\n                              host='localhost', database='displayad')\\ncursor = cnx.cursor()\\n\\n@app.route('/upload', methods=['POST'])\\ndef upload():\\n  # Get the form data\\n  ad_name = request.form['ad_name']\\n  ad_description = request.form['ad_description']\\n  ad_file = request.files['ad_file']\\n\\n  # Save the file to the file system\\n  ad_file.save(os.path.join('/home/hemang/Downloads/notebook_scripts/displyaAdData', ad_file.filename))\\n\\n  # Insert the data into the database\\n  query = 'INSERT INTO ads (name, description, file) VALUES (%s, %s, %s)'\\n \\n\"\n    },\n    {\n        \"message\": \"It looks like there is an error occurring when you try to access the /upload route of your Flask application. This error could be caused by a number of issues, such as a syntax error in the Python code that defines the route, a problem with the template file that is being rendered, or an issue with the data being passed to the template.To troubleshoot this error, you can try the following steps:Check the log messages in the terminal window where the Flask application is running. This may provide more information about the cause of the error.Enable debugging in the Flask application by setting the debug parameter of the Flask constructor to True. This will cause Flask to display more detailed error messages when an error occurs.Copy codeapp = Flask(__name__, debug=True)\\nReview the code that defines the /upload route and make sure that it is correct and that there are no syntax errors. You may also want to check the upload.html template file to make sure that it is correctly formatted and that there are no errors in the template syntax.Check the form data that is being passed to the /upload route when you submit the advertisement upload form. Make sure that all required fields are being filled out and that the form is being submitted correctly.\",\n        \"response\": \"If the name of your Flask backend is flaskBackend.py, you can run it by using the following command:Copy codepython flaskBackend.py\\nThis will start the Flask development server, and you will be able to access the upload.html form and submit data to the backend.Keep in mind that the above code is just a skeleton of the complete solution. You will need to add error handling and additional logic as needed for your specific use case.\"\n    },\n    {\n        \"message\": \"please help me create the page `upload.html` \",\n        \"response\": \"To add CSS to your HTML, you can include a <link> element in the <head> of your HTML file that points to the CSS file:Copy code<head>\\n  <link rel=\\\"stylesheet\\\" href=\\\"/path/to/style.css\\\">\\n</head>\\nYou can also include the CSS directly in the HTML file by using a <style> element in the <head> of the file:Copy code<head>\\n  <style>\\n    /* Your CSS goes here */\\n  </style>\\n</head>\\nAlternatively, you can include the CSS in a separate file and include it in the HTML file using a <link> element as shown above. This is a good practice as it keeps the HTML and CSS code separate and easier to maintain.Once you have added the CSS, you can apply styles to the elements in your HTML by using the appropriate selectors. For example:Copy codebody {\\n  background-color: lightblue;\\n}\\n\\nh1 {\\n  color: white;\\n  text-align: center;\\n}\\n\\np {\\n  font-family: verdana;\\n  font-size: 20px;\\n}\\nThis CSS code will apply a light blue background color to the <body> element, white text color to the <h1> element, and a Verdana font with a size of 20px to the <p> element.You can learn more about CSS by reading online tutorials or books, or by experimenting with different styles and seeing how they affect the appearance of your HTML elements.\"\n    },\n    {\n        \"message\": \"Here is an example of what the upload.html template file might look like for your project:Copy code<html>\\n  <head>\\n    <title>Upload an advertisement</title>\\n  </head>\\n  <body>\\n    <h1>Upload an advertisement</h1>\\n    <form action=\\\"/upload\\\" method=\\\"post\\\" enctype=\\\"multipart/form-data\\\">\\n      <label for=\\\"file\\\">Advertisement file:</label>\\n      <input type=\\\"file\\\" name=\\\"file\\\" id=\\\"file\\\" required>\\n      <br>\\n      <label for=\\\"start_time\\\">Start time:</label>\\n      <input type=\\\"datetime-local\\\" name=\\\"start_time\\\" id=\\\"start_time\\\" required>\\n      <br>\\n      <label for=\\\"end_time\\\">End time:</label>\\n      <input type=\\\"datetime-local\\\" name=\\\"end_time\\\" id=\\\"end_time\\\" required>\\n      <br>\\n      <input type=\\\"submit\\\" value=\\\"Submit\\\">\\n    </form>\\n  </body>\\n</html>\\nThis template file defines an HTML form that allows the user to upload an advertisement file and specify the start and end times for the advertisement. When the form is submitted, it will send a POST request to the /upload route of the Flask application, which will handle the uploaded advertisement file and save it to a local directory.You may need to modify this template file to suit the specific requirements of your project, such as the layout and functionality of the user interface and the logic for handling UPI payments and bid-based ad scheduling.Once you have created the template file and placed it in the templates directory, the Flask application should be able to locate it and render it correctly when the /upload route is accessed.\",\n        \"response\": \"To add the CSS to upload.html and home.html, you can include a <link> element in the <head> of each HTML file that points to the CSS file. For example:Copy code<head>\\n  <link rel=\\\"stylesheet\\\" href=\\\"/path/to/style.css\\\">\\n</head>\\nMake sure to replace /path/to/style.css with the actual path to your CSS file.Alternatively, you can include the CSS directly in the HTML file using a <style> element as described in the previous answer.Keep in mind that the <link> element should be included in the <head> of both upload.html and home.html if you want the styles to be applied to both files.Once you have added the <link> element or <style> element to the <head> of your HTML files, the styles defined in the CSS file will be applied to the elements in the HTML file.For example, if you have the following CSS code in your style.css file:Copy codebody {\\n  background-color: lightblue;\\n}\\n\\nh1 {\\n  color: white;\\n  text-align: center;\\n}\\n\\np {\\n  font-family: verdana;\\n  font-size: 20px;\\n}\\nAnd you include a <link> element in the <head> of upload.html and home.html that points to style.css, the styles defined in the CSS file will be applied to the <body>, <h1>, and <p> elements in both upload.html and home.html.You can learn more about CSS and how to style your HTML elements by reading online tutorials or books, or by experimenting with different styles and seeing how they affect the appearance of your HTML elements.\"\n    },\n    {\n        \"message\": \"Please help me create a database that can store the required ad data that is uploaded by the user and integrate it with `upload.html` file.\",\n        \"response\": \"To give your HTML elements a material design look using CSS, you can use the Google Material Design Lite (MDL) library. This library provides a set of CSS styles and components that follow the material design guidelines and can be easily applied to your HTML elements to give them a consistent and professional look.To use the MDL library, you will need to include a <link> element in the <head> of your home.html and upload.html files that points to the MDL CSS file. You can do this by adding the following line to the <head> of both home.html and upload.html:Copy code<link rel=\\\"stylesheet\\\" href=\\\"https://fonts.googleapis.com/icon?family=Material+Icons\\\">\\n<link rel=\\\"stylesheet\\\" href=\\\"https://code.getmdl.io/1.4.1/material.orange-amber.min.css\\\">\\nThis will include the MDL CSS file in your HTML files, and you will be able to use the MDL styles and components to style your HTML elements.To use the MDL styles, you will need to add the appropriate class names to your HTML elements. For example, to give an element the \\\"mdl-button\\\" style, you can add the class mdl-button to the element:Copy code<button class=\\\"mdl-button mdl-js-button mdl-button--raised\\\">\\n  Click me\\n</button>\\nYou can find more information about the MDL styles and components, as well as examples of how to use them, in the MDL documentation: https://getmdl.io/components/index.htmlKeep in mind that the MDL library is just one way to give your HTML elements a material design look using CSS. There are also other libraries and frameworks that provide similar functionality, such as Materialize and Material-UI. You can choose the one that best fits your needs and preferences.\"\n    },\n    {\n        \"message\": \"To create a database to store the advertisement data uploaded by the user, you will need to use a database management system (DBMS) such as MySQL, PostgreSQL, or SQLite.Here is an example of how you can create a MySQL database and table to store the advertisement data using Python:Copy codeimport mysql.connector\\n\\n# Connect to the MySQL server\\ncnx = mysql.connector.connect(user='your_username', password='your_password', host='localhost', database='your_database')\\n\\n# Create a cursor object to execute SQL statements\\ncursor = cnx.cursor()\\n\\n# Create the advertisement table\\ntable_sql = \\\"\\\"\\\"\\nCREATE TABLE advertisement (\\n  id INT(11) NOT NULL AUTO_INCREMENT,\\n  file_name VARCHAR(255) NOT NULL,\\n  file_path VARCHAR(255) NOT NULL,\\n  start_time DATETIME NOT NULL,\\n  end_time DATETIME NOT NULL,\\n  PRIMARY KEY (id)\\n);\\n\\\"\\\"\\\"\\ncursor.execute(table_sql)\\n\\n# Commit the changes to the database\\ncnx.commit()\\n\\n# Close the cursor and connection\\ncursor.close()\\ncnx.close()\\nThis code creates a MySQL database named your_database, and a table called advertisement within it. The advertisement table has columns for storing the file name, file path, start time, and end time of the advertisement.Once you have created the database and table, you can use Python and SQL statements to insert the advertisement data into the table when the user submits the advertisement upload form.Here is an example of how you can insert the advertisement data into the advertisement table using Python:Copy codeimport mysql.connector\\n\\n# Connect to the MySQL server\\ncnx = mysql.connector.connect(user='your_username', password='your_password', host='localhost', database='your_database')\\n\\n# Create a cursor object to execute SQL statements\\ncursor = cnx.cursor()\\n\\n# Insert the advertisement data into the table\\ninsert_sql = \\\"INSERT INTO advertisement (file_name, file_path, start_time, end_time) VALUES (%s, %s, %s, %s)\\\"\\ncursor.execute(insert_sql, (file_name, file_path, start_time, end_time))\\n\\n# Commit the changes to the database\\ncnx.commit()\\n\\n# Close the cursor and connection\\ncursor.close()\\ncnx.close()\\nThis code inserts a row into the advertisement table with the values for the file name, file path, start time, and end time that are passed to the execute function.To integrate the database with the upload.html template file, you will need to modify the Flask route that handles the submission of the advertisement upload form to include the logic for connecting to the database, inserting the advertisement data, and committing the changes. You will also need to make sure that the required Python modules (such as mysql-connector-python) are installed and imported in your Flask application.I hope this helps! Let me know if you have any questions or need further assistance with integrating the database with your Flask application.\",\n        \"response\": \"To add an animated fluid gradient background to your home.html and upload.html files, you can use a combination of HTML, CSS, and JavaScript.Here is one way to do this:In the <head> of your home.html and upload.html files, include the following <style> element to define the gradient background:Copy code<style>\\n  body {\\n    background: linear-gradient(-45deg, #ee7752, #e73c7e, #23a6d5, #23d5ab);\\n    background-size: 400% 400%;\\n    animation: gradientBG 20s ease infinite;\\n  }\\n\\n  @keyframes gradientBG {\\n    0% {\\n      background-position: 0% 50%;\\n    }\\n    50% {\\n      background-position: 100% 50%;\\n    }\\n    100% {\\n      background-position: 0% 50%;\\n    }\\n  }\\n</style>\\nThis will create a gradient background that animates between four different colors over a 20-second period. You can adjust the colors, duration, and easing of the animation by modifying the values in the linear-gradient, background-size, and animation properties.To ensure that the gradient background animates smoothly on all devices, you may want to include the following JavaScript code in the <head> of your home.html and upload.html files:Copy code<script>\\n  // Check if the browser supports the requestAnimationFrame API\\n  if (window.requestAnimationFrame) {\\n    // Use the requestAnimationFrame API to animate the gradient background\\n    var updateBodyBG = function () {\\n      window.requestAnimationFrame(updateBodyBG);\\n      document.body.style.backgroundPosition = \\\"0% \\\" + (window.pageYOffset / 2) + \\\"px\\\";\\n    };\\n    updateBodyBG();\\n  }\\n</script>\\nThis code will use the requestAnimationFrame API to update the background position of the body element as the page is scrolled, creating a parallax effect.You can find more information about the requestAnimationFrame API and how to use it to create smooth animations in this tutorial: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/window/requestAnimationFrameI hope this helps! Let me know if you have any questions or need further assistance.\"\n    },\n    {\n        \"message\": \"when I tried to install mysql python library it gives me this error.\\n```\\nCollecting mysql\\n  Downloading mysql-0.0.3-py3-none-any.whl (1.2 kB)\\nCollecting mysqlclient\\n  Downloading mysqlclient-2.1.1.tar.gz (88 kB)\\n     \\u2501\\u2501\\u2501\\u2501\\u2501\\u2501\\u2501\\u2501\\u2501\\u2501\\u2501\\u2501\\u2501\\u2501\\u2501\\u2501\\u2501\\u2501\\u2501\\u2501\\u2501\\u2501\\u2501\\u2501\\u2501\\u2501\\u2501\\u2501\\u2501\\u2501\\u2501\\u2501\\u2501\\u2501\\u2501\\u2501\\u2501\\u2501\\u2501 88.1/88.1 kB 199.5 kB/s eta 0:00:00a 0:00:01\\n  Preparing metadata (setup.py) ... error\\n  error: subprocess-exited-with-error\\n  \\n  \\u00d7 python setup.py egg_info did not run successfully.\\n  \\u2502 exit code: 1\\n  \\u2570\\u2500> [16 lines of output]\\n      /bin/sh: 1: mysql_config: not found\\n      /bin/sh: 1: mariadb_config: not found\\n      /bin/sh: 1: mysql_config: not found\\n      Traceback (most recent call last):\\n        File \\\"<string>\\\", line 2, in <module>\\n        File \\\"<pip-setuptools-caller>\\\", line 34, in <module>\\n        File \\\"/tmp/pip-install-52_hrbam/mysqlclient_9fc80ae5b6e647049860bc76ae99d0a1/setup.py\\\", line 15, in <module>\\n          metadata, options = get_config()\\n        File \\\"/tmp/pip-install-52_hrbam/mysqlclient_9fc80ae5b6e647049860bc76ae99d0a1/setup_posix.py\\\", line 70, in get_config\\n          libs = mysql_config(\\\"libs\\\")\\n        File \\\"/tmp/pip-install-52_hrbam/mysqlclient_9fc80ae5b6e647049860bc76ae99d0a1/setup_posix.py\\\", line 31, in mysql_config\\n          raise OSError(\\\"{} not found\\\".format(_mysql_config_path))\\n      OSError: mysql_config not found\\n      mysql_config --version\\n      mariadb_config --version\\n      mysql_config --libs\\n      [end of output]\\n  \\n  note: This error originates from a subprocess, and is likely not a problem with pip.\\nerror: metadata-generation-failed\\n\\n\\u00d7 Encountered error while generating package metadata.\\n\\u2570\\u2500> See above for output.\\n\\nnote: This is an issue with the package mentioned above, not pip.\\nhint: See above for details.\\nNote: you may need to restart the kernel to use updated packages.\\n```\",\n        \"response\": \"To make your animated fluid gradient background more dramatic and eye-catching, you can try the following techniques:Use more vibrant and contrasting colors: You can use more vibrant and contrasting colors in your gradient to create a more striking visual effect. For example, you might try using a gradient that transitions between bright shades of red, orange, yellow, green, blue, and purple.Use a larger number of colors: Instead of using a gradient with just four colors, you can try using a gradient with six or more colors to create a more complex and varied visual effect. You can experiment with different color combinations and arrangements to find the one that looks best to you.Use a more complex gradient pattern: Instead of using a simple linear gradient, you can try using a more complex gradient pattern such as a radial gradient or a conic gradient. These types of gradients can create more intricate and dynamic visual effects, especially when combined with a large number of colors.Use a longer or shorter animation duration: You can adjust the duration of the animation to create a faster or slower gradient transition. A shorter duration will create a faster, more energetic effect, while a longer duration will create a slower, more relaxed effect.Use a different easing function: You can use a different easing function in your animation to create a different visual effect. For example, you can use the ease-in-out easing function to create a smooth, gradual acceleration and deceleration, or you can use the ease-out easing function to create a more abrupt, bouncy effect.To give your gradient background a material design look, you might also want to consider using color combinations and gradients that are inspired by the Google Material Design color palette. You can find more information about the Material Design color system and how to use it to create harmonious and visually appealing color schemes in this guide: https://material.io/design/color\"\n    },\n    {\n        \"message\": \"It looks like you are encountering an error while installing the mysqlclient module, which is a Python library for connecting to MySQL databases.The error message mentions that the mysql_config utility was not found. This utility is used by the mysqlclient module to determine the compile-time options and linking information for the MySQL client library, which is needed to build the module.To fix this error, you will need to install the MySQL development files on your system. On Ubuntu, you can install the development files by running the following command:Copy codesudo apt-get install default-libmysqlclient-dev\\nOn CentOS, you can install the development files by running the following command:Copy codesudo yum install mysql-devel\\nOn other Linux distributions, the package name may be different. You can search for the package name using your package manager, or consult the documentation for your distribution for more information.Once you have installed the MySQL development files, try installing the mysqlclient module again. It should be able to find the mysql_config utility and build the module successfully.I hope this helps! Let me know if you have any questions or need further assistance with installing the mysqlclient module.\",\n        \"response\": \"Here is some CSS code that you can use to create an animated fluid gradient background with a material design look:Copy codebody {\\n  background: linear-gradient(45deg, #2196f3, #f44336);\\n  background-size: 400% 400%;\\n  animation: gradient-animation 15s ease infinite;\\n}\\n\\n@keyframes gradient-animation {\\n  0% {\\n    background-position: 0% 50%;\\n  }\\n  50% {\\n    background-position: 100% 50%;\\n  }\\n  100% {\\n    background-position: 0% 50%;\\n  }\\n}\\nThis code will create a gradient that transitions between two shades of blue and red, inspired by the Google Material Design color palette. The gradient will animate over a 15 second duration, using a smooth ease easing function. The animation will loop indefinitely.You can customize this code to use different colors and animation settings as needed. For example, to use a six-color gradient with a longer animation duration and a more complex easing function, you could use the following code:Copy codebody {\\n  background: linear-gradient(45deg, #2196f3, #f44336, #9c27b0, #ffeb3b, #4caf50, #03a9f4);\\n  background-size: 600% 600%;\\n  animation: gradient-animation 30s ease-in-out infinite;\\n}\\n\\n@keyframes gradient-animation {\\n  0% {\\n    background-position: 0% 50%;\\n  }\\n  25% {\\n    background-position: 100% 50%;\\n  }\\n  50% {\\n    background-position: 100% 100%;\\n  }\\n  75% {\\n    background-position: 0% 100%;\\n  }\\n  100% {\\n    background-position: 0% 50%;\\n  }\\n}\\nThis code will create a gradient that transitions between six shades of blue, purple, yellow, orange, red, and green, and animates over a 30 second duration using the ease-in-out easing function. The animation will also loop indefinitely.You can find more information about the CSS linear-gradient function and how to use it to create gradients with multiple colors in this guide: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/CSS/\"\n    },\n    {\n        \"message\": \"phpmyadmin gives me this error when I try to login. ` Failed to set session cookie. Maybe you are using HTTP instead of HTTPS to access phpMyAdmin.`\",\n        \"response\": \"To make the gradient curved and changing rotations, you can use the radial-gradient function in your CSS. Here is an example of how you can use it to create a curved gradient that rotates:Copy codebody {\\n  background: radial-gradient(circle at center, #FF0000 0%, #0000FF 100%) fixed;\\n  background-size: cover;\\n  animation: rotate 10s linear infinite;\\n}\\n\\n@keyframes rotate {\\n  100% {\\n    transform: rotate(360deg);\\n  }\\n}\\nTo make the gradient change shapes, you can use the conic-gradient function. Here is an example of how you can use it to create a conical gradient that changes shapes:Copy codebody {\\n  background: conic-gradient(#FF0000 0%, #0000FF 100%) fixed;\\n  background-size: cover;\\n  animation: change-shape 10s linear infinite;\\n}\\n\\n@keyframes change-shape {\\n  0% {\\n    transform: rotate(0deg);\\n  }\\n  50% {\\n    transform: rotate(180deg);\\n  }\\n  100% {\\n    transform: rotate(360deg);\\n  }\\n}\\nYou can customize the colors, transition times, and shapes of the gradient by adjusting the values in the CSS code above.To make the gradient in a trendy material design look, you can use the Material Design color palette and incorporate it into your gradient. Here is an example of how you can use the Material Design color palette to create a gradient:Copy codebody {\\n  background: linear-gradient(to right, #6200EE 0%, #03DAC5 100%) fixed;\\n  background-size: cover;\\n}\\nYou can use a tool like Material Design Palette to generate a customized color palette for your gradient.\"\n    },\n    {\n        \"message\": \"It looks like you are trying to access phpMyAdmin using HTTP instead of HTTPS, and the server is unable to set the session cookie.To fix this error, you will need to access phpMyAdmin using HTTPS. To do this, you will need to make sure that you have an SSL certificate installed on your server and that the web server is configured to use HTTPS for the phpMyAdmin URL.If you are using Apache as your web server, you can enable HTTPS by adding the following lines to your Apache configuration file (usually located at /etc/apache2/apache2.conf or /etc/httpd/conf/httpd.conf):Copy codeLoadModule ssl_module modules/mod_ssl.so\\n\\n<VirtualHost _default_:443>\\n  ServerName your_server_name\\n  DocumentRoot /usr/share/phpmyadmin\\n  SSLEngine on\\n  SSLCertificateFile /path/to/your/ssl/certificate.crt\\n  SSLCertificateKeyFile /path/to/your/ssl/private/key.key\\n  <Directory /usr/share/phpmyadmin>\\n    AllowOverride All\\n  </Directory>\\n</VirtualHost>\\nMake sure to replace your_server_name with the actual hostname or IP address of your server, and /path/to/your/ssl/certificate.crt and /path/to/your/ssl/private/key.key with the actual paths to your SSL certificate and private key files.Once you have added these lines to your Apache configuration file, you will need to restart the Apache web server for the changes to take effect. On Ubuntu, you can restart Apache using the following command:Copy codesudo service apache2 restart\\nOn CentOS, you can restart Apache using the following command:Copy codesudo service httpd restart\\nAfter restarting Apache, you should be able to access phpMyAdmin using HTTPS by visiting the URL https://your_server_name/phpmyadmin in your web browser.I hope this helps! Let me know if you have any questions or need further assistance with enabling HTTPS for phpMyAdmin.\",\n        \"response\": \"Here is a combined CSS code that includes all the features you requested: a curved, rotating gradient with changing shapes and a material design color palette:Copy codebody {\\n  background: conic-gradient(#6200EE 0%, #03DAC5 100%) fixed;\\n  background-size: cover;\\n  animation: rotate 10s 