ut field, and will update the value of the file-path input field with the selected file's path whenever the file is changed.Note that in order to use the PyScript code, you need to wrap it inside a py-script element.\"\n    },\n    {\n        \"message\": \"To complete the CSS code snippet for schedule.html so that it looks like home.html and uplaod.html, you can add the following styles:Copy code/* Table styles */\\ntable {\\n  border-collapse: collapse;\\n  width: 100%;\\n}\\n\\nth, td {\\n  text-align: left;\\n  padding: 8px;\\n}\\n\\ntr:nth-child(even) {\\n  background-color: #f2f2f2;\\n}\\n\\nth {\\n  background-color: #4caf50;\\n  color: white;\\n}\\n\\n/* Form styles */\\ninput[type=text], select, textarea {\\n  width: 100%;\\n  padding: 12px;\\n  border: 1px solid #ccc;\\n  border-radius: 4px;\\n  box-sizing: border-box;\\n  margin-top: 6px;\\n  margin-bottom: 16px;\\n  resize: vertical;\\n}\\n\\ninput[type=submit] {\\n  background-color: #4caf50;\\n  color: white;\\n  padding: 12px 20px;\\n  border: none;\\n  border-radius: 4px;\\n  cursor: pointer;\\n}\\n\\ninput[type=submit]:hover {\\n  background-color: #45a049;\\n}\\n\\n.container {\\n  border-radius: 5px;\\n  background-color: #f2f2f2;\\n  padding: 20px;\\n}\\nThis should give you the desired styles for the schedule.html page. You can add these styles below the styles you have already written in your CSS file.\",\n        \"response\": \"The error message ModuleNotFoundError: No module named 'browser' indicates that the browser module is not found. This error occurs because the browser module is not part of the Python standard library, and it is not available in PyScript by default.To fix this error, you need to include the browser module in your code by importing it at the beginning of your Python script. You can do this by adding the following line at the top of your script:Copy codefrom browser import document, window\\nAlternatively, you can also import the document and window objects separately, like this:Copy codefrom browser import document\\nfrom browser import window\\nOnce you have imported the browser module, you should be able to access the document and window objects and use them in your code.I hope this helps! Let me know if you have any further questions.\"\n    },\n    {\n        \"message\": \"I want to add top navigation bar to `schedule.html` as given in `uplaod.html`\",\n        \"response\": \"You can use the !pip install command inside the <py-script> element to install a package. For example:Copy code<py-script>\\n  !pip install package_name\\n</py-script>\\nNote that this will install the package only for the current session. If you want to permanently install the package, you will need to use the !pip install command outside of the <py-script> element, in the terminal or command prompt.Alternatively, you can use the pyodide.load_package() function to load a package from PyPi. This function takes the name of the package as an argument and returns a Promise that resolves when the package is loaded. For example:Copy code<py-script>\\n  from pyodide import load_package\\n\\n  def load_my_package():\\n    load_package('package_name').then(lambda: print('Package loaded successfully!'))\\n\\n  load_my_package()\\n</py-script>\\nThis will load the package permanently, and it will be available in all future sessions.Keep in mind that not all packages are compatible with PyScript, so you may need to install a package that has been compiled to WebAssembly (WASM) in order for it to work. You can find a list of compatible packages on the PyScript website.\"\n    },\n    {\n        \"message\": \"To add a top navigation bar to your schedule.html file, you can use the following CSS code:Copy code/* Navigation bar styles */\\n.navbar {\\n  overflow: hidden;\\n  background-color: #333;\\n  position: fixed;\\n  top: 0;\\n  width: 100%;\\n}\\n\\n.navbar a {\\n  float: left;\\n  display: block;\\n  color: #f2f2f2;\\n  text-align: center;\\n  padding: 14px 16px;\\n  text-decoration: none;\\n  font-size: 17px;\\n}\\n\\n.navbar a:hover {\\n  background-color: #ddd;\\n  color: black;\\n}\\n\\n.navbar a.active {\\n  background-color: #4caf50;\\n  color: white;\\n}\\nTo use this navigation bar, you will need to add a nav element with a class of \\\"navbar\\\" to the top of your schedule.html file, like this:Copy code<nav class=\\\"navbar\\\">\\n  <a href=\\\"#\\\">Home</a>\\n  <a href=\\\"#\\\">About</a>\\n  <a href=\\\"#\\\">Contact</a>\\n</nav>\\nYou can then add links to your navigation bar by adding a elements inside the nav element. Make sure to replace the href attribute with the appropriate URL for each link.I hope this helps! Let me know if you have any questions.\",\n        \"response\": \"It looks like the pyodide.load_package method is not available in the version of Pyodide that you are using.One solution could be to update to the latest version of Pyodide by using the following line of code:Copy code!pip install --upgrade pyodide\\nThis will install the latest version of Pyodide and its dependencies, which might include the load_package method.Alternatively, you could try using the pyodide.load function instead of load_package. This function allows you to load a package by name and returns a promise that resolves when the package has finished loading.For example:Copy codefrom pyodide import load\\n\\ndef load_my_package():\\n    load('browser').then(lambda: print('Package loaded successfully!'))\\n\\nload_my_package()\\nfrom browser import document, html\\n\\ndef update_file_path(event):\\n    file_path = event.target.value\\n    document[\\\"file-path\\\"].value = file_path\\n\\ndocument[\\\"ad_file\\\"].bind(\\\"change\\\", update_file_path)\\nI hope this helps! Let me know if you have any questions or if there is anything else I can help with.\"\n    },\n    {\n        \"message\": \"Currently `schedule.html` looks like below.\\n\\n```html\\n<!DOCTYPE html>\\n<html>\\n<head>\\n  <link rel=\\\"stylesheet\\\" 