ation property to redirect the user's browser to the GitHub login page URL.Here's the updated code for the click event listener for the \\\"Login with GitHub\\\" button:Copy code// Add a click event listener to the \\\"Login with GitHub\\\" button\\ndocument.getElementById(\\\"login-button\\\").addEventListener(\\\"click\\\", function() {\\n  // Redirect the user to the GitHub login page\\n  window.location = \\\"https://github.com/login\\\";\\n});\\nAlternatively, you can use the window.open() function to open the GitHub login page in a new tab or window.Copy code// Add a click event listener to the \\\"Login with GitHub\\\" button\\ndocument.getElementById(\\\"login-button\\\").addEventListener(\\\"click\\\", function() {\\n  // Open the GitHub login page in a new tab or window\\n  window.open(\\\"https://github.com/login\\\");\\n});\\nThis should open the GitHub login page when the \\\"Login with GitHub\\\" button is clicked.\"\n    },\n    {\n        \"message\": \"Give me code snippet to replace in my current file as a solution of the step number 1.\",\n        \"response\": \"To store the token after logging in, you will need to implement a way to handle the authentication flow. Here is an example of how you could do this:Modify the popup.html file to include an iframe element that will be used to display the GitHub login page:Copy code<!-- Add an iframe element to display the GitHub login page -->\\n<iframe id=\\\"login-iframe\\\" src=\\\"https://github.com/login\\\"></iframe>\\nModify the popup.js file to listen for messages from the iframe element and store the token if it is received:Copy code// Listen for messages from the iframe element\\nwindow.addEventListener(\\\"message\\\", function(event) {\\n  // Check if the message is a token\\n  if (event.data.type == \\\"auth_token\\\") {\\n    // Store the token in local storage\\n    localStorage.setItem(\\\"auth_token\\\", event.data.authToken);\\n  }\\n});\\nModify the content_script.js file to send the token to the popup.js file after the user has logged in:Copy code// Send the authentication token to the popup\\nwindow.opener.postMessage({\\n  type: \\\"auth_token\\\",\\n  authToken: \\\"AUTH_TOKEN\\\"\\n}, \\\"*\\\");\\nYou will also need to modify the popup.js file to handle the case where the user is already logged in and the token is stored in local storage. In this case, you can simply retrieve the token from local storage and send it to the background script to publish the chat.I hope this helps! Let me know if you have any questions.\"\n    },\n    {\n        \"message\": \"To solve the error that you're encountering, you should replace the following lines in your fetch_data function:Copy codeimport jsonify\\n\\n...\\n\\nreturn str(json_data)\\nwith:Copy codefrom flask import jsonify\\n\\n...\\n\\nreturn jsonify(results)\\nThis will correctly return the results list as a JSON response to the client. The jsonify function is a Flask helper function that converts a Python object (e.g. a list, dictionary) into a JSON response.Note: Make sure to remove the import jsonify line as it is causing an error because it is trying to import a module that doesn't exist. You should only keep the from flask import jsonify line.\",\n        \"response\": \"Here is an example of how you could modify popup.html to implement step 1:Copy code<!DOCTYPE html>\\n<html>\\n  <head>\\n    <title>ChatGPTPublish</title>\\n  </head>\\n  <body>\\n    <!-- Add a button to login with GitHub -->\\n    <button id=\\\"login-button\\\">Login with GitHub</button>\\n    <!-- Add a form to select the repository and enter the auth token -->\\n    <form id=\\\"publish-form\\\">\\n      <!-- Add radio buttons to select the repository -->\\n      <input type=\\\"radio\\\" id=\\\"repository-1\\\" name=\\\"repository\\\" value=\\\"USERNAME/REPO1\\\">\\n      <label for=\\\"repository-1\\\">Repository 1</label><br>\\n      <input type=\\\"radio\\\" id=\\\"repository-2\\\" name=\\\"repository\\\" value=\\\