 advertisement</option>\\n                <option value=\\\"video\\\">Video advertisement</option>\\n              </select>\\n              <label>Type of advertisement</label>\\n            </div>\\n            <div class=\\\"file-field input-field\\\">\\n              <div class=\\\"btn\\\">\\n                <span>Select a file</span>\\n                <input type=\\\"file\\\" id=\\\"ad_file\\\" name=\\\"ad_file\\\" required>\\n              </div>\\n              <div class=\\\"file-path-wrapper\\\">\\n                <input class=\\\"file-path validate\\\" type=\\\"text\\\" placeholder=\\\"Upload file\\\">\\n              </div>\\n            </div>\\n            <div class=\\\"input-field\\\">\\n              <input type=\\\"submit\\\" value=\\\"Submit\\\" class=\\\"btn\\\">\\n            </div>\\n          </form>\\n        </div>\\n      </div>\\n    </div>\\n  </div>\\n</div>\\nTo display the actual path of the selected file, you will need to use JavaScript to get the path and update the value of the file path input field. Here's an example of how to do it:Copy code<script>\\n  document.querySelector(\\\"#ad_file\\\").addEventListener(\\\"change\\\", function() {\\n    document.querySelector(\\\".file-path\\\").value = this.value;\\n  });\\n</script>\\nThis script listens for the \\\"change\\\" event on the file input field and updates the value of the file path input field with the selected file's path when the event is triggered.You can add this script to the main-content.html file, after the file input field.\",\n        \"response\": \"It looks like the empty entry at the end of the settings table is being added by the code that is responsible for inserting the settings into the database. One possible cause of this issue is that the code is not properly handling the case where some of the settings are not included in the request payload.To fix this problem, you could modify the save_setting route to check for the presence of each setting in the request payload before inserting it into the database. Here is an example of how you could do this:Copy code@app.route('/save_setting', methods=['POST'])\\ndef save_setting():\\n    # Get the data from the request payload\\n    data = request.get_json()\\n\\n    # Get the settings from the request data\\n    settings = data['settings']\\n\\n    # Connect to the database\\n    connection = mysql.connector.connect(\\n        user='root', password='mysql123!@#', host='localhost',\\n        database='displayad'\\n    )\\n    cursor = connection.cursor()\\n\\n    # Construct the INSERT INTO statement\\n    insert_statement = 'INSERT INTO setting (parameter, value) VALUES (%s, %s)'\\n\\n    # Execute the statement for each setting\\n    for parameter, value in settings.items():\\n        # Skip the setting if it is not present in the request payload\\n        if value is None:\\n            continue\\n        cursor.execute(insert_statement, (parameter, value))\\n\\n    # Commit the changes to the database\\n    connection.commit()\\n    cursor.close()\\n    connection.close()\\n\\n    # Return a success response\\n    return '', 200\\nThis code will check for the presence of each setting in the settings dictionary before inserting it into the database. If a setting is not present in the dictionary, it will be skipped and not added to the database.\"\n    },\n    {\n        \"message\": \"I want to use pyscript instead of the javascript. Please give me code for pyscript for ```<script>\\n  document.querySelector(\\\"#ad_file\\\").addEventListener(\\\"change\\\", function() {\\n    document.querySelector(\\\".file-path\\\").value = this.value;\\n  });\\n</script>\\n```\",\n        \"response\": \"To update the value of a row in a MySQL table based on the value of a column, you can use the UPDATE statement with a WHERE clause. For example, if you want to update the value of the value column in the settings table for a row with a specific parameter, you can use the following query:Copy codeUPDATE settings\\nSET value = %s\\nWHERE parameter = %s\\nHere, %s is a placeholder for the new value and the parameter name, respectively. These values should be passed as a tuple as the second argument to the cursor.execute() method.You can also use the INSERT ... ON DUPLICATE KEY UPDATE statement to insert a new row into the table if a row with the same parameter does not exist, or update the value of an existing row if a row with the same parameter does exist. This can be useful if you want to avoid making multiple queries to the database.For example, you can use the following query to insert a new row or update the value of an existing row:Copy codeINSERT INTO settings (parameter, value) VALUES (%s, %s)\\nON DUPLICATE KEY UPDATE value = VALUES(value)\\nHere, the ON DUPLICATE KEY UPDATE clause specifies that if a row with the same parameter already exists in the table, the value of the value column should be updated to the value provided in the VALUES(value) expression.To implement this in your Flask app, you can modify the save_setting route as follows:Copy code@app.route('/save_setting', methods=['POST'])\\ndef save_setting():\\n    # Get the data from the request payload\\n    settings = request.get_json()\\n\\n    # Connect to the database\\n    connection = mysql.connector.connect(\\n        user='root', password='mysql123!@#', host='localhost',\\n        database='displayad'\\n    )\\n    cursor = connection.cursor()\\n\\n    # Construct the INSERT ... ON DUPLICATE KEY UPDATE statement\\n    insert_statement = '''\\n    INSERT INTO setting (parameter, value) VALUES (%s, %s)\\n    ON DUPLICATE KEY UPDATE value = VALUES(value)\\n    '''\\n\\n    # Execute the statement for each setting\\n    for parameter, value in settings.items():\\n        cursor.execute(insert_statement, (parameter, value))\\n\\n    # Commit the changes to the database\\n    connection.commit()\\n    cursor.close()\\n    connection.close()\\n\\n    # Return a success response\\n    return '', 200\\nThis will update the value of an existing row with the\"\n    },\n    {\n        \"message\": \"To use a Python script instead of JavaScript, you can use the Flask framework to handle the file input and update the file path value in the HTML.Here's an example of how you can do this:Copy codefrom flask import Flask, request, render_template\\n\\napp = Flask(__name__)\\n\\n@app.route('/upload', methods=['GET', 'POST'])\\ndef upload():\\n    if request.method == 'POST':\\n        file = request.files['ad_file']\\n        file_path = file.filename\\n        return render_template('main-content.html', file_path=file_path)\\n    return render_template('main-content.html')\\n\\nif __name__ == '__main__':\\n    app.run()\\nIn your main-content.html template, you can then display the file path value using Jinja syntax:Copy code<div class=\\\"file-path-wrapper\\\">\\n  <input class=\\\"file-path validate\\\" type=\\\"text\\\" value=\\\"{{ file_path }}\\\">\\n</div>\\nThis way, when the form is submitted and the file input is processed by the Flask app, the file path value will be updated in the HTML template.\",\n        \"response\": \"To update the value of a particular parameter if its entry already exists in the setting table, you can use the UPDATE statement in your MySQL query. Here is an example of how you can modify your save_setting function to achieve this:Copy code@app.route('/save_setting', methods=['POST'])\\ndef save_setting():\\n    # Get the data from the request payload\\n    settings = request.get_json()\\n\\n    # Connect to the database\\n    connection = mysql.connector.connect(\\n        user='root', password='mysql123!@#', host='localhost',\\n        database='displayad'\\n    )\\n    cursor = connection.cursor()\\n\\n    # Construct the UPDATE statement\\n    update_statement = '''\\n    UPDATE setting SET value = %s WHERE parameter = %s\\n    '''\\n\\n    # Execute the statement for each setting\\n    for parameter, value in settings.items():\\n        if(parameter!=''):\\n            cursor.execute(update_statement, (value, parameter))\\n\\n    # Commit the changes to the database\\n    connection.commit()\\n    cursor.close()\\n    connection.close()\\n\\n    # Return a success response\\n    return '', 200\\nNote that this will update the value of a particular parameter if it exists in the setting table, and will not create a new entry if it does not exist. If you want to create a new entry if the parameter does not exist, you can use the INSERT INTO ... ON DUPLICATE KEY UPDATE statement as follows:Copy code@app.route('/save_setting', methods=['POST'])\\ndef save_setting():\\n    # Get the data from the request payload\\n    settings = request.get_json()\\n\\n    # Connect to the database\\n    connection = mysql.connector.connect(\\n        user='root', password='mysql123!@#', host='localhost',\\n        database='displayad'\\n    )\\n    cursor = connection.cursor()\\n\\n    # Construct the INSERT INTO ... ON DUPLICATE KEY UPDATE statement\\n    insert_statement = '''\\n    INSERT INTO setting (parameter, value) VALUES (%s, %s)\\n    ON DUPLICATE KEY UPDATE value = VALUES(value)\\n    '''\\n\\n    # Execute the statement for each setting\\n    for parameter, value in settings.items():\\n        if(parameter!=''):\\n            cursor.execute(insert_statement, (parameter, value))\\n\\n    # Commit the changes to the database\\n    connection.commit()\\n    cursor.close()\\n    connection.close()\\n\\n    # Return a success response\\n    return '', 200\\nThis will update the value of a particular parameter if it exists in the setting table, and will create a new entry if it does not exist.\"\n    },\n    {\n        \"message\": \"I want to add pyscript in client-side .\",\n        \"response\": \"To achieve this, you can use the INSERT ... ON DUPLICATE KEY UPDATE statement in your MySQL query. This statement allows you to insert a new row into the table if the specified primary key or unique index value does not already exist in the table, or update the existing row if the value already exists.Here's an example of how you can use this statement in your save_setting function to update the value of a parameter if it already exists in the setting table, or insert a new row if it does not exist:Copy code@app.route('/save_setting', methods=['POST'])\\ndef save_setting():\\n    # Get the data from the request payload\\n    settings = request.get_json()\\n\\n    # Connect to the database\\n    connection = mysql.connector.connect(\\n        user='root', password='mysql123!@#', host='localhost',\\n        database='displayad'\\n    )\\n    cursor = connection.cursor()\\n\\n    # Construct the INSERT ... ON DUPLICATE KEY UPDATE statement\\n    insert_statement = '''\\n    INSERT INTO setting (parameter, value) VALUES (%s, %s)\\n    ON DUPLICATE KEY UPDATE value = VALUES(value)\\n    '''\\n\\n    # Execute the statement for each setting\\n    for parameter, value in settings.items():\\n        cursor.execute(insert_statement, (parameter, value))\\n\\n    # Commit the changes to the database\\n    connection.commit()\\n    cursor.close()\\n    connection.close()\\n\\n    # Return a success response\\n    return '', 200\\nThis code will insert a new row into the setting table if the parameter value does not already exist in the table, or update the existing row if the parameter value already exists.Note: In this example, we are assuming that the parameter column has a unique index applied to it, so that there are no duplicate values in the column. If this is not the case in your table, you may need to modify the query to use a different column or combination of columns as the unique index.\"\n    },\n    {\n        \"message\": \"It is not possible to use Python on the client-side in a web browser, as the web browser can only execute JavaScript. If you want to execute some Python code on the client-side, you will need to use a tool like Pyodide to compile it to WebAssembly and execute it in the browser. However, this is not a common approach and is not recommended unless you have a specific need for it.If you want to update the value of the file-path input field based on the selected file, you can use JavaScript to achieve this. Here is the equivalent code in JavaScript:Copy codedocument.querySelector(\\\"#ad_file\\\").addEventListener(\\\"change\\\", function() {\\n  document.querySelector(\\\".file-path\\\").value = this.value;\\n});\\nThis code adds an event listener to the ad_file input field that listens for the change event, which is fired when the value of the input field changes. When the event is triggered, the code sets the value of the file-path input field to the value of the ad_file input field.You can include this code in your HTML file by placing it in a script element:Copy code<script>\\n  document.querySelector(\\\"#ad_file\\\").addEventListener(\\\"change\\\", function() {\\n    document.querySelector(\\\".file-path\\\").value = this.value;\\n  });\\n</script>\\nMake sure to place the script element after the elements it references, such as the ad_file and file-path input fields.\",\n        \"response\": \"To create a table with a unique index on the parameter column, you can use the following SQL statement:Copy codeCREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS setting (\\n    id INT AUTO_INCREMENT PRIMARY KEY,\\n    parameter VARCHAR(255) NOT NULL,\\n    value VARCHAR(255) NOT NULL,\\n    UNIQUE (parameter)\\n);\\nTo add a unique index to an existing table, you can use the following SQL statement:Copy codeALTER TABLE setting ADD UNIQUE (parameter);\\nKeep in mind that this will only work if the parameter column does not already contain any duplicate values. If there are duplicate values, you will need to either remove the duplicates or modify the unique index to allow for duplicates before adding the index.Once you have added the unique index, you can use the following INSERT INTO ... ON DUPLICATE KEY UPDATE statement to either insert a new row or update an existing row with the same parameter value:Copy codeINSERT INTO setting (parameter, value) VALUES (%s, %s)\\nON DUPLICATE KEY UPDATE value = VALUES(value)\\nYou can use this statement in your save_setting function like this:Copy code@app.route('/save_setting', methods=['POST'])\\ndef save_setting():\\n    # Get the data from the request payload\\n    settings = request.get_json()\\n\\n    # Connect to the database\\n    connection = mysql.connector.connect(\\n        user='root', password='mysql123!@#', host='localhost',\\n        database='displayad'\\n    )\\n    cursor = connection.cursor()\\n\\n    # Construct the INSERT ... ON DUPLICATE KEY UPDATE statement\\n    insert_statement = '''\\n    INSERT INTO setting (parameter, value) VALUES (%s, %s)\\n    ON DUPLICATE KEY UPDATE value = VALUES(value)\\n    '''\\n\\n    # Execute the statement for each setting\\n    for parameter, value in settings.items():\\n        cursor.execute(insert_statement, (parameter, value))\\n\\n    # Commit the changes to the database\\n    connection.commit()\\n    cursor.close()\\n    connection.close()\\n\\n    # Return a success response\\n    return '', 200\\n\"\n    },\n    {\n        \"message\": \"I hate javascript. Please never ever suggest me any javascript code. alaways give me pyscript code instead alaways in the future . thank you.\",\n        \"response\": \"It looks like there is an issue with the settings dictionary that is being returned by the get_settings function. In the current implementation, the dictionary keys are the IDs of the rows in the setting table, while the values are the values of the value column.To fix this issue, you can modify the get_settings function to return a dictionary that has the parameter column values as the keys and the value column values as the values.Here is an example of how you can modify the get_settings function to do this:Copy code@app.route('/get_settings', methods=['GET'])\\ndef get_settings