iles in the head of the document. Check that the URLs are correct and that the files are hosted on a reliable source.Check that the Materialize library is being loaded after the jQuery library. Materialize is built on top of jQuery, so it needs to be loaded after jQuery.Make sure that you have properly initialized the dropdown menus. In your script, you can use the M.Dropdown.init function to initialize the dropdowns. This should be called after the DOM has finished loading. For example:Copy codedocument.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', function() {\\n  var dropdownElements = document.querySelectorAll('.dropdown-trigger');\\n  M.Dropdown.init(dropdownElements, {});\\n});\\nIf you are using a template engine, such as Jinja, make sure that you are correctly rendering the dropdown menus in the HTML. The select element should have the dropdown-trigger class, and there should be a ul element with the dropdown-content class that contains the options for the dropdown.Check the console for any errors or warnings that might be causing the dropdown menus to not work correctly.I hope this helps! Let me know if you have any further questions.\"\n    },\n    {\n        \"message\": \"\\nJsException(PythonError: Traceback (most recent call last): File \\\"/lib/python3.10/site-packages/_pyodide/_base.py\\\", line 429, in eval_code .run(globals, locals) File \\\"/lib/python3.10/site-packages/_pyodide/_base.py\\\", line 300, in run coroutine = eval(self.code, globals, locals) File \\\"\\\", line 1, in ModuleNotFoundError: No module named 'browser' )\",\n        \"response\": \"There could be several reasons why the dropdown menus are not showing up after including the Materialize library. Here are a few things you can try to troubleshoot the issue:Make sure that you have properly linked the Materialize CSS and JavaScript files in the head of your HTML document. Check that the URLs are correct and that the files are hosted on a stable and accessible location.Make sure that you ha