s)\\\"\\n    cursor.execute(insert_query, (start_time, end_time, ad_name, ad_description, file.filename))\\n    cnx.commit()\\nThis code will check if the ads table exists in the displayad database, and if it doesn't, it will create the table before inserting the ad data. This should prevent the error from occurring.\",\n        \"response\": \"There is no syntax error in the delete_ad function in flaskBackend.py. However, it's possible that the error message you mentioned could be caused by the fact that the route for this function is not registered in your Flask application.To fix this error, you need to make sure that the delete_ad function is registered as a route in your Flask application. You can do this by adding the following code at the end of your flaskBackend.py file:Copy codeif __name__ == '__main__':\\n    app.run(debug=True)\\nThis will run the Flask application and register all the routes defined in the file. You should now be able to access the delete_ad function by making a DELETE request to the /delete-ad/<id> route.Additionally, it's possible that there could be other issues causing the error message you mentioned, such as a problem with the database connection or a problem with the SQL query being executed by the function. You might want to check for these issues as well.\"\n    },\n    {\n        \"message\": \"I am running phpmyadmin in docker using http protocol on 8080 port but it does not display in https. can you help me make changes to docker container to access it through https?\",\n        \"response\": \"It looks like the deleteAd function is making an HTTP DELETE request to the /delete-ad/<id> endpoint when the delete button is clicked. The id parameter is passed in as an argument to the function, and it is included in the URL of the request using template literals.To handle this DELETE request in the backend, you can use a route decorator in your Flask application to specify that this endpoint should accept DELETE requests. Here is an example of how you can do this:Copy code@app.route('/delete-ad/<int:id>', methods=['DELETE'])\\ndef delete_ad(id):\\n    # Connect to the database and delete the ad with the specified id\\n    # You can use a MySQL DELETE statement here\\n    # Be sure to commit the delete operation and close the connection to the database\\n    return '', 204\\nThis function should receive the id of the ad to delete as an argument, and it should connect to the database to delete the ad with that id. You can use a MySQL DELETE statement to delete the ad from the ads table. Remember to commit the delete operation and close the connection to the database when you are finished.Finally, you should return an HTTP response with a status code of 204 (No Content) to indicate that the request was successful and there is no additional content to send back to the client.\"\n    },\n    {\n        \"message\": \"To access your PHPMyAdmin installation through HTTPS, you'll need to use an HTTP reverse proxy that can handle SSL/TLS encryption and decryption. One popular choice for this is Nginx.Here is an example of how you can set up Nginx as an HTTP reverse proxy for your PHPMyAdmin installation running in Docker:First, you'll need to create a directory on your host machine to store the Nginx configuration files and SSL/TLS certificate and key files. For example, you can create a directory called nginx in your home directory:Copy codemkdir ~/nginx\\nNext, you'll need to generate an SSL/TLS certificate and key pair for your domain. You can use a tool like OpenSSL to do this. For example:Copy codeopenssl req -x509 -nodes -days 365 -newkey rsa:2048 -keyout ~/nginx/nginx.key -out ~/nginx/nginx.crt\\nThis will generate a self-signed SSL/TLS certificate and key pair that is valid for 365 days. Replace ~/nginx with the path to the directory you created in step 1, and replace nginx.key and nginx.crt with the filenames you want to use for the key and certificate files, respectively.Create a new Nginx configuration file for your PHPMyAdmin installation. You can use the following configuration as a starting point:Copy codeserver {\\n    listen 443 ssl;\\n    server_name example.com;\\n    ssl_certificate /etc/nginx/ssl/nginx.crt;\\n    ssl_certificate_key /etc/nginx/ssl/nginx.key;\\n\\n    location / {\\n        proxy_pass http://phpmyadmin:8080;\\n        proxy_set_header Host $host;\\n        proxy_set_header X-Real-IP $remote_addr;\\n        proxy_set_header X-Forwarded-For $proxy_add_x_forwarded_for;\\n        proxy_set_header X-Forwarded-Proto $scheme;\\n    }\\n}\\nReplace example.com with the domain name you want to use for your PHPMyAdmin installation. Make sure to also update the paths to the SSL/TLS certificate and key files to match the filenames you used in step 2. Save the file as phpmyadmin.conf in the nginx directory you created in step 1.Start the Nginx container and mount the nginx directory as a volume:Copy codedocker run -d -p 443:443 -v ~/nginx:/etc/nginx/ssl:ro --name nginx nginx\\nThis will start the Nginx container and bind it to the host's HTTPS port (443). It will also mount the nginx directory as a read-only volume at /etc/nginx/ssl in the container, so that Nginx can access the SSL/TLS certificate and key files.Restart your PHPMyAdmin container with the following command:Copy codedocker restart phpmyadmin\\nYou should now be able to access your PHPMyAdmin installation through HTTPS using your domain name. For example:Copy codehttps://example.com\\n\",\n        \"response\": \"To delete a record from a MySQL table using the id field, you can use the DELETE statement with a WHERE clause that specifies the id value:Copy codeDELETE FROM table_name WHERE id = value;\\nFor example, to delete a record from a table called ads where the id field is 3, you can use the following query:Copy codeDELETE FROM ads WHERE id = 3;\\nThis will delete the record with id 3 from the ads table. If you want to delete multiple records at once, you can specify a list of id values in the WHERE clause:Copy codeDELETE FROM ads WHERE id IN (1, 2, 3, 4);\\nThis will delete all records with id values of 1, 2, 3, and 4 from the ads table.It's important to note that the DELETE statement is permanent and cannot be undone, so be careful when using it. If you want to update or modify a record rather than deleting it, you can use the UPDATE statement.\"\n    },\n    {\n        \"message\": \"what is https default port?\",\n        \"response\": \"To add an Edit and Delete button to the tbody element in schedule.html, you can modify the code inside the loop that creates the table rows as follows:Copy codefor (var i = 0; i < data.length; i++) {\\n  var ad = data[i];\\n  var row = document.createElement(\\\"tr\\\");\\n  row.innerHTML = \\\"<td>\\\" + ad.id + \\\"</td>\\\" +\\n                 \\\"<td>\\\" + ad.ad_start_time + \\\"</td>\\\" +\\n                 \\\"<td>\\\" + ad.ad_end_time + \\\"</td>\\\" +\\n                 \\\"<td>\\\" + ad.ad_name + \\\"</td>\\\" +\\n                 \\\"<td>\\\" + ad.ad_description + \\\"</td>\\\" +\\n                 \\\"<td>\\\" + ad.file_name + \\\"</td>\\\" +\\n                 \\\"<td><button class='btn edit-btn' data-id='\\\" + ad.id + \\\"'>Edit</button>\\\" +\\n                 \\\"<button class='btn delete-btn' data-id='\\\" + ad.id + \\\"'>Delete</button></td>\\\";\\n  document.getElementById(\\\"ads-table-body\\\").appendChild(row);\\n}\\nThis will add a column to the table with Edit and Delete buttons for each row. You can then handle the click events for these buttons using JavaScript to open the modal for editing or to send a DELETE request to the server to delete the ad.Here is an example of how you can handle the click event for the Delete button:Copy codedocument.querySelectorAll('.delete-btn').forEach(button => {\\n  button.addEventListener('click', event => {\\n    // Get the id of the ad to delete\\n    var id = event.target.dataset.id;\\n    // Send a DELETE request to the server to