<td>{{ ad.id }}</td>\\n    <td>{{ ad.ad_start_time }}</td>\\n    <td>{{ ad.ad_end_time }}</td>\\n    <td>{{ ad.ad_name }}</td>\\n    <td>{{ ad.ad_description }}</td>\\n    <td>{{ ad.file_name }}</td>\\n    <td>\\n      <button class=\\\"btn\\\" onclick=\\\"editAd({{ ad.id }})\\\">Edit</button>\\n      <button class=\\\"btn red\\\" onclick=\\\"deleteAd({{ ad.id }})\\\">Delete</button>\\n    </td>\\n  </tr>\\n  {% endfor %}\\n</tbody>\\nYou can then use Flask routes to handle the HTTP requests for deleting and editing ads. For example, to delete an ad with a specific id, you can define a route like this:Copy code@app.route('/delete-ad/<int:id>', methods=['DELETE'])\\ndef delete_ad(id):\\n    # Connect to the database\\n    cnx = mysql.connector.connect(user='root', password='mysql123!@#', host='localhost', database='displayad')\\n    cursor = cnx.cursor()\\n    # Delete the ad with the specified id\\n    cursor.execute(f'DELETE FROM ads WHERE id={id}')\\n    cnx.commit()\\n    cursor.close()\\n    cnx.close()\\n    return '', 204\\nYou can then make a DELETE request to this route using an XMLHttpRequest in JavaScript or an ajax function in jQuery:Copy codefunction deleteAd(id) {\\n    $.ajax({\\n        url: `/delete-ad/${id}`,\\n        type: 'DELETE',\\n        success: function(result) {\\n            // Refresh the table to show the updated data\\n            fetchData();\\n        }\\n    });\\n}\\n\"\n    },\n    {\n        \"message\": \"for running phpmyadmin I don't want to use nginx. I already have apache2 running as web server. I want to use apache2 as web server\",\n        \"response\": \"To replace the JavaScript code with Python, you can create a Python script that generates the HTML code for the table rows with the Delete and Edit buttons. Then, you can use the render_template function in your Flask backend to return this generated HTML code to the client.Here is an example of how you can do this:In your Flask backend, create a Python function that generates the HTML code for the table rows with the Delete and Edit buttons. This function should take in a list of ads as an argument and return the generated HTML code as a string:Copy codedef generate_table_rows(ads):\\n    rows = ''\\n    for ad in ads:\\n        row = f\\\"<tr>\\\" +\\n              f\\\"<td>{ad.id}</td>\\\" +\\n              f\\\"<td>{ad.ad_start_time}</td>\\\" +\\n              f\\\"<td>{ad.ad_end_time}</td>\\\" +\\n              f\\\"<td>{ad.ad_name}</td>\\\" +\\n              f\\\"<td>{ad.ad_description}</td>\\\" +\\n              f\\\"<td>{ad.file_name}</td>\\\" +\\n              f\\\"<td><button onclick='deleteAd({ad.id})'>Delete</button></td>\\\" +\\n              f\\\"<td><button onclick='editAd({ad.id})'>Edit</button></td>\\\" +\\n              f\\\"</tr>\\\"\\n        rows += row\\n    return rows\\nIn your Flask route that handles the /fetchdata request, fetch the data from the database, generate the HTML code for the table rows using the function you just created, and return it to the client:Copy code@app.route('/fetchdata')\\ndef fetch_data():\\n    # Connect to the database\\n    cnx = mysql.connector.connect(user='root', password='mysql123!@#', host='localhost', database='displayad')\\n    cursor = cnx.cursor()\\n    # Fetch the ads from the database\\n    cursor.execute('SELECT * FROM ads')\\n    ads = cursor.fetchall()\\n    cursor.close()\\n    cnx.close()\\n    # Generate the HTML code for the table rows\\n    table_rows = generate_table_rows(ads)\\n    # Return the HTML code to the client\\n    return render_template('schedule.html', table_rows=table_rows)\\nIn your schedule.html file, replace the JavaScript code in the tbody element with the Python code that generates the table rows:Copy code<tbody id=\\\"ads-table-body\\\">\\n    <!-- Python script will populate this table -->\\n    {{ table_rows }}\\n</tbody>\\nThis should allow you to replace the JavaScript code with Python in your schedule.html file. Let me know if you hav