ow these steps:Stop the MySQL server if it is\"\n    },\n    {\n        \"message\": \"There is no syntax error in the delete_ad function in flaskBackend.py. However, it's possible that the error message you mentioned could be caused by the fact that the route for this function is not registered in your Flask application.To fix this error, you need to make sure that the delete_ad function is registered as a route in your Flask application. You can do this by adding the following code at the end of your flaskBackend.py file:Copy codeif __name__ == '__main__':\\n    app.run(debug=True)\\nThis will run the Flask application and register all the routes defined in the file. You should now be able to access the delete_ad function by making a DELETE request to the /delete-ad/<id> route.Additionally, it's possible that there could be other issues causing the error message you mentioned, such as a problem with the database connection or a problem with the SQL query being executed by the function. You might want to check for these issues as well.\",\n        \"response\": \"running. You can do this by running the following command:Copy code```\\nsudo service mysql stop\\n```\\n2. Start the MySQL server in safe mode with the --skip-grant-tables option. This will allow you to bypass the authentication process and gain access to the MySQL prompt without a password:Copy code```\\nsudo mysqld_safe --skip-grant-tables &\\n```\\n3. Connect to the MySQL prompt by running the following command:Copy code```\\nmysql -u root\\n```\\n4. Update the root user password by running the following SQL query:Copy code```\\nUPDATE mysql.user SET password=PASSWORD('your_new_password') WHERE User='root';\\n```\\n5. Flush the privileges so that the changes take effect:Copy code```\\nFLUSH PRIVILEGES;\\n```\\n6. Exit the MySQL prompt:Copy code```\\nexit\\n```\\n7. Stop the MySQL server:Copy code```\\nsudo service mysql stop\\n```\\n8. Start the MySQL server in normal mode:Copy code```\\nsudo service mysql start\\n```\\nYou should now be able to connect to the MySQL server using the root user and your new password.Note: If you are using MySQL version 8.0 or later, you may need to use the authentication_string column instead of the password column in step 4. In this case, the SQL query would be:Copy codeALTER USER 'root'@'localhost' IDENTIFIED BY 'your_new_password';\\n\"\n    },\n    {\n        \"message\": \"  function deleteAd(id) {\\n    fetch(`/delete-ad/${id}`, {method: 'DELETE'})\\n      .then(response => {\\n        if (response.ok) {\\n          // Refresh the table to show the updated data\\n          fetchData();\\n        }\\n      });\\n  }\",\n        \"response\": \"If the MariaDB server is running with the --skip-grant-tables option, it means that all authentication checks are skipped and any user can connect to the server without a password. To reset the root password in this case, you will need to stop the MariaDB server and start it with the --skip-grant-tables option disabled. Here are the steps to reset the root password in this case:Stop the MariaDB server. On most systems, you can use the following command:Copy codesudo systemctl stop mariadb\\nStart the MariaDB server with the --skip-grant-tables option disabled and the --init-file option to run a script to reset the root password. The following command will start the server and run the reset_root_password.sql script to reset the root password to newpassword:Copy codesudo mysqld_safe --init-file=/path/to/reset_root_password.sql &\\nOnce the server has started, use the mysql command-line client to connect to the server and set the root password to newpassword. Run the following commands:Copy codemysql -u root\\nSET PASSWORD FOR 'root'@'localhost' = PASSWORD('newpassword');\\nStop the MariaDB server and start it normally:Copy codesudo systemctl stop mariadb\\nsudo systemctl start mariadb\\nTest the new root password by connecting to the MariaDB server with the mysql command-line client:Copy c