ng query:Copy codeDELETE FROM ads WHERE id = 3;\\nThis will delete the record with id 3 from the ads table. If you want to delete multiple records at once, you can specify a list of id values in the WHERE clause:Copy codeDELETE FROM ads WHERE id IN (1, 2, 3, 4);\\nThis will delete all records with id values of 1, 2, 3, and 4 from the ads table.It's important to note that the DELETE statement is permanent and cannot be undone, so be careful when using it. If you want to update or modify a record rather than deleting it, you can use the UPDATE statement.\",\n        \"response\": \"It appears that there is no code in this file to actually retrieve and display the data from the database. In order to display the data, you will need to make an HTTP request to fetch the data from the server and then use JavaScript to add the data to the table.One way to do this would be to use the fetch function to make an HTTP request to the server to retrieve the data. You can then use the then method to specify a callback function to be executed once the data has been retrieved. Inside the callback function, you can use JavaScript to add the data to the table.Here is an example of how you could do this:Copy code// Make an HTTP GET request to the server to retrieve the data\\nfetch('/fetchdata')\\n  .then(response => response.json()) // Convert the response to a JSON object\\n  .then(data => {\\n    // Loop through the data and add each item to the table\\n    data.forEach(item => {\\n      var row = document.createElement(\\\"tr\\\");\\n      row.innerHTML = `\\n        <td>${item.id}</td>\\n        <td>${item.ad_start_time}</td>\\n        <td>${item.ad_end_time}</td>\\n        <td>${item.ad_name}</td>\\n        <td>${item.ad_description}</td>\\n        <td>${item.file_name}</td>\\n      `;\\n      document.getElementById(\\\"ads-table-body\\\").appendChild(row);\\n    });\\n  });\\nThis code will make an HTTP GET request to the server at the /fetchdata endpoint, retrieve the data as a JSON object, and then loop through the data and add each item to the table.You will also need to modify the fetchdata.py script to return the data as a JSON object, rather than printing it to the console. To do this, you can use the jsonify function from the Flask library to convert the data to a JSON object and return it as the response to the HTTP request.Here is an example of how you could do this:Copy codefrom flask import Flask, jsonify\\n\\n# ...\\n\\n# Convert the list to a JSON object and return it as the response to the request\\nreturn jsonify(results)\\nWith these changes, the data should be displayed in the table on the schedule webpage.\"\n    },\n    {\n        \"message\": \"here is how `schedule.html` file looks like as given below.\\n\\n```html\\n<!DOCTYPE html>\\n<html>\\n<head>\\n  <link rel=\\\"stylesheet\\\" href=\\\"https://cdnjs.cloudflare.com/ajax/libs/materialize/1.0.0/css/materialize.min.css\\\">\\n  <title>Ad Schedule</title>\\n  <style>\\n  body {\\n    margin: 0;\\n    font-family: Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif;\\n  }\\n\\n  /* Navigation bar styles */\\n  .navbar {\\n    overflow: hidden;\\n    background-color: #333;\\n    position: fixed;\\n    top: 0;\\n    width: 100%;\\n  }\\n\\n  .navbar a {\\n    float: left;\\n    display: block;\\n    color: #f2f2f2;\\n    text-align: center;\\n    padding: 14px 16px;\\n    text-decoration: none;\\n    font-size: 17px;\\n  }\\n\\n  .navbar a:hover {\\n    background-color: #ddd;\\n    color: black;\\n  }\\n\\n  .navbar a.active {\\n    background-color: #4caf50;\\n    color: white;\\n  }\\n\\n  .main {\\n    padding: 16px;\\n    margin-top: 30px;\\n    height: 1500px; /* Used in this example to enable scrolling */\\n  }\\n\\n  /* Modal styles */\\n  .modal {\\n    display: none; /* Hidden by default */\\n    position: fixed; /* Stay in place */\\n    z-index: 1; /* Sit on top */\\n    padding-top: 100px; /* Location of the box */\\n    left: 0;\\n    top: 0;\\n    width: 100%; /* Full width */\